Compiler optimization techniques can be broadly classified into two categories: static and dynamic.
Static optimization techniques are applied during the compilation phase, before the program is executed. These techniques analyze the code and make changes to improve its performance without executing it. Some popular static optimization techniques include:
Dead code elimination: This technique removes code that is never executed, such as code that is unreachable or code that is executed only in certain conditions that are never met.
Constant folding: This technique replaces expressions that evaluate to a constant value with the constant value itself, which can improve the performance of the program.
Loop unrolling: This technique unrolls loops by duplicating the code inside the loop and executing it multiple times, which can improve the performance of the program.

Just-in-time compilation: This technique compiles the code at runtime, which allows the compiler to optimize the code based on the specific input data and execution environment.
Profile-guided optimization: This technique uses profiling information to optimize the code based on the most frequently executed code paths.
Speculative execution: This technique executes code that is likely to be executed in the future, which can improve the performance of the program.
